Q:	I’m wondering if you might reflect for one last moment about what this interview, here today, has been like for you, what your thoughts and feelings about the interview were. 
A:	It just made me kinda think. The interview was fine. It just made me go back and think about different things in life.

A:	Yeah, refreshed. Refreshed me again, remember where I came from and where I’m at, where I am today.

Q:	Are there any thoughts or feelings that you had during the interview, or how the interview has affected you, or any comments about the interview?
A:	I just like doin’ this because I want somebody else to … I want to be able to reach out to somebody else that life might be in some form or fashion like mine. 
Q:	Really, kind of, give back and give some perspective. 
A:	Feedback of what I went through and stuff.
Q:	Help through research.
A:	Yup, help with research, yup.
Q:	That’s awesome. And do you … did you have any particular feelings or thoughts during the interview other than that? 
A:	No, not at all. I always had a good experience with these interviews. 
Q:	That’s awesome, I’m so glad to hear it. That’s great! 
A:	And you guys have the … the two female that have came, you and … at first I was like, “Ugh.” You know what I’m sayin’. 
Q:	Yeah, about having someone in your house.
A:	But I’ve had … we’ve cracked up, we laughed, we did everything, you know. 
Q:	It’s fun! It’s a fun thing to do. I love …
A:	It is a fun thing.
Q:	Yeah, I love hearing, like, people’s stories because they’re so powerful. 
A:	Right and it’s amazing what different people’s been through in life. 
Q	And how they handle it.
A:	And it makes you think like, “Damn. That person was worse than me.”
Q:	Yeah, and they’re strong. Like, it’s, like, it’s so interesting how …
A:	I think that the more you go through the stronger you get. 
Q:	Yeah, absolutely. It’s amazing how powerful people are.

A:	The impact it has on me … it was pleasure that you guys are doing this for the women. I mean, that’s really a really awesome thing and maybe it helps relieve some of the pain and some of the, you know, daily struggles and it makes ‘em reflect on what they did in the past and how it’s gonna change it for the future. I guess that’s it and that you girls are awesome [laughs].

A:	To be honest, no. I think this pretty well says it all. You know, it’s just something that you, you know, remember and something that was then and this is now. Yeah. Yeah. 
Q:	I like it. Alright, well that you so much for sharing all that information.
A:	Thank you! You are so awesome.

SCRIPT:  Thank you for this interview. I have just one more question for you. Many of the stories you have told me are about experiences that stand out from the day-to-day. For example, we talked about a high point, a turning point, a scene about your health, etc. Given that most people don’t share their life stories in this way on a regular basis, I’m wondering if you might reflect for one last moment about what this interview, here today, has been like for you.  
Q:	What were your thoughts and feelings during the interview?  
Q:	So I’m wondering when you reflect on these moments about the interview, what are your thoughts and feelings? What were your thoughts and feelings during the interview?
A:	Oh, damn it, she made me cry again [laughs]. Like, I just, I don’t know, I guess I’ve done such a good job of pushing everything away, and putting up this façade that life is wonderful and great, because I do a good job of lyin’ about it, because I don’t want … I …. I will be damned if people know that I am that, you know, I … I have allowed myself to become that woman. You know what I mean? And I have. I have masters, I don’t have a significant other. I’m not equal, I’m less than, and I am ashamed of what I’ve let myself become, because I did it once, and I knew better. And I did it again. Just, you know, shh, go with the flow, just it’ll … to let it go through, it’ll pass by. But I am extremely unhappy, and life is too short to be unhappy. I just want to be happy, and I don’t, you know, he can’t be happy either. We don’t fight, we don’t spend time together, I don’t plan on keepin’ [Child L] from him, but then if I tell him that I … I’m trying to talk to him seriously about it, he’ll quit his job, and he’s comin’ home, and he’s gonna … yeah, because that’s how mature you, and then that’ll be my fault that you quit your job, and you’re not gonna let me go anywhere. I’ll have to call the police. I’ve had to call em twice since we lived here. He did somethin’ to my car so it wouldn’t start, when me and my mom … oh yeah. And then he … when he hit my car like that, they did nothing. He hit … he put the car drive, floored it, and hit my car on the passenger side, back door, right where my son was sitting, because I gave somebody a ride that was broken down. I have completely neutral, didn’t know what was going on, and I was so sorry. I felt so stupid. He’s like, “let me the fuck outta here.” And he walked again. I don’t know, all of sudden, he walked home. 
Q:	How do you think this interview has affected you?  
Q:	How do you think the interview has affected you?
A:	I am emotionally drained.
Q:	I’m sorry!
A:	I do. I feel like ahh, but it’s quiet, too, so – I don’t get that very often. 
Q:	You might be a little relieved. 
A:	I don’t, I don’t listen to the radio in the car anymore, ‘cause that’s my only peace, ‘cause he’s watching the trees, or the deer, or the cows, or whatever. Unless he’s whippin’ shit at my head. He’s got a heck of an arm.
Q:	Oh, [Woman 105].
A:	He’s got a … I don’t even know what to do. He knocked me out with a taco truck! Out cold, and I woke up with his finger in my belly button that are … diggin’ in my belly button. That’s what woke me up, like, he … I don’t know how long I was out, just a few minutes, but he chipped my tooth, and knocked his tooth out. He is mean, he will … anything in this house is a weapon, anything. I have loaded toys up and got rid of them, because I was tired of being assaulted by them. All his heavy trucks were gone for a long time, and … and he – no bats, and balls. All his guns are gone, because the other day he shot me in the eye with his nerf gun, and said, “Got her in the eye. Yes!”
Q:	No he didn’t.
A:	Yes he did. That’s why those targets are up there. Only shoot the targets, and he was stood on that side of the kitchen and shot me – over there cookin’, I went to turn around, went to turn around, and it went “Whop” Eye open and all, right in the eye. The next day he shot me in the other eye. I mean, what’s the chances of a little gun … little Nerf bullet that … right in the damn eye, like … and he was like, “Yes, got her in the eye.” I couldn’t believe it.
Q:	Do you have any other comments about the interview process?
Q:	And my last question, do you have any other comments about the interview, the interview process?
A:	I just love the interviewer! She is the most wonderful person in the world, and should probably have to do this, like, every other week. 
Q:	You’re so sweet. 
A:	I love you. In fact, I got some stuff for you. I gotta give it to you.

A:	That’s a good question. 
Q:	[Laughs].
A:	I would say that … I would say I enjoyed it. It was different, a little different as far as the questions because some bring … some brought back a lot of memory, you know, and then, you know, through things that I still couldn’t talk about because I don’t … you know what I’m saying? That it is like I … that’s the reason when you see me thinking, it’s like, okay I be thinking … I be thinking of something because I want to get it out, but then it’s some still hold that part back, like, oh you don’t, you know. So … and like I said, I feel comfortable, you know, so if I ever … if I ever have an interview with you again, and you know, you might … you might don’t even ask a question and I might just get to talk to you because it like … you know, you feel … I can, you know how you … how you say?
Q:	Cause’ you know me a little bit more?
A:	Right.
Q:	Mhmm (yes). You’re familiar; we’re familiar with each other.
A:	I’m familiar with you, so it’s like, okay I think I can trust her on this. Q:	So you opened up in the interview?
A:	Yes. 
Q:	Well thank you, I do appreciate it because I know you don’t know me.
A:	Yes, yes. I really … I really have because like I said, as far as my children … I think … I think it’s first … in any one of my interviews, I think they based … they don’t even know nothing about my kids got tooken from me at all. I’m not for sure. I know they know I have nine children, you know, but … I think one of my interviews got they names, you know, cause’ I gave them they names and stuff like that. But they … I haven’t even got that far with them and that felt good because … because I don’t too much talk, you know, about something like that.

A:	It’s good to talk about it ‘cause I don’t talk to people about this stuff. You know, not … certain family members, but I rarely talk to my family members ‘cause we argue. He don’t even know everything, you know. He just … I … I … I’m slow at openin’ my door to him, you know. And which he wants to know, he wants to be there to hug me if I’m cryin’, or, you know, if I’m upset about the kids, but I’m the type that will close my door and don’t want to talk to anybody. Or I’ll go inside and cry in the bathroom, and get myself together, you know what I’m sayin’? 
Q:	Yeah.
A:	I could just say, it felt good ‘cause I needed to get it off my chest. I need this talk like this, you know what I’m sayin’, to somebody that ain’t gonna be judgmental. And family will do that to you. They will judge you from the time you open your mouth to the time you close it. They find somethin’ wrong with what you had to say. I don’t … I don’t even talk to my mom about it. We don’t talk about nothin’ like that. We talk … only … every time I speak to her, we talkin’ about my sisters and what they done did wrong. Or she’ll be like, “Oh, [Niece L] did good at her volleyball game today.” And stuff like that about my nieces. Other than that, she’ll try to call and tell me she talked to my kids and that they said tell mommy we love her, and stuff like that. Other than that, that’s it. 
Q:	How do you think this interview has affected you?  
Q:	So what effect do you think the interview had on you?
A:	I’m up … I woke up kinda pissed off. I’m alright today, I’m alright now [laughs].
Q:	I’m glad our conversation helped [laughs].
A:	I’m alright now, for real [laughs].
Q:	Do you have any other comments about the interview process?
Q:	And do you have any other comments about the interview process, or the questions?
A:	I had fun talkin’ to you [laughs].
Q:	I’m glad [laughs] ‘cause I know it’s a little lengthy, but I feel like it’s a really great interview. 
A:	Mhmm (yes), me too. I … I needed to get most of that off my chest. ‘cause I was like, “Lord,” – I be wanting to tell my boyfriend a lot, but then I’ll be like, “No, it’s too soon. It’s only been five months.” 
Q:	And that’s understandable.
A:	I’ll scare the man away [laughs].
Q:	Well not even scare him, but it’s just, like, really intimate, you know, things to tell someone. 
A:	Yeah, it’s personal. And not to know if the relationship is really gonna … and then you know all my business. You know what I mean, shoot [laughs]. And then I’ll feel, like, crazy ‘cause I done told you everything.

I mean I look … I see it, in there another way, like, now, like, “Okay, well I ain’t look at it that way” or “I ain’t ever think of it like that.” Yeah, so it could be something I could go home and use, you know? A:	 No.

But … it’s helped me to understand that just because, I don’t know, just because you make mistakes, or whatever, you can help other people realize “Hey, just because you did this does not mean that you are a bad person. You can pick yourself up and start again.” I am very happy with the person I am today, and I’m still improving every day. I wouldn’t change my background or my history for anything. 
Q:	‘Cause you learned so much.
A:	Even the bad parts, the parts that I just wanted to give up and die, yeah they bug me, they bug me a lot, but it’s part of what makes you, you. It’s part of your story. You’re stuck with it. It don’t matter, like I said, I wouldn’t change it for anything.

Like, when you were asking me those memory … memorable questions, I had to, like, really think there. I was like, “Huh? What?” But, no it was really good. It was like a brain exercise. 
Q:	[Laughs].
A:	It was really good. 
Q:	Good. It was nice to see how far you’ve come? 
A:	Yeah, from … from when I first started to now. Just because it’s been a few years, or whatever, since I’ve had one of these, I … all these questions still bring up, all the questions that they’ve asked before, and when I’ve answered. So it helped me progress and see how much I’ve come.

A:	Me too.
